      "name": "",
      "username": "Alex",
      "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.trainerday.com/alex/{size}/1331_2.png",
      "created_at": "2023-10-20T14:05:56.274Z",
      "cooked": "<p>I see this screen.<br>\n<div class=\"lightbox-wrapper\"><a class=\"lightbox\" href=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/original/2X/2/28406c7273a5f5d1897a7f962581816e6da96bb3.jpeg\" data-download-href=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/28406c7273a5f5d1897a7f962581816e6da96bb3\" title=\"image\"><img src=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/optimized/2X/2/28406c7273a5f5d1897a7f962581816e6da96bb3_2_684x499.jpeg\" alt=\"image\" data-base62-sha1=\"5K57NxkFsuyzzIsxXSyj0WOnOhB\" width=\"684\" height=\"499\" srcset=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/optimized/2X/2/28406c7273a5f5d1897a7f962581816e6da96bb3_2_684x499.jpeg, https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/original/2X/2/28406c7273a5f5d1897a7f962581816e6da96bb3.jpeg 1.5x, https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/original/2X/2/28406c7273a5f5d1897a7f962581816e6da96bb3.jpeg 2x\" data-small-upload=\"https://forums.trainerday.com/uploads/default/optimized/2X/2/28406c7273a5f5d1897a7f962581816e6da96bb3_2_10x10.png\"><div class=\"meta\"><svg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-far-image svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><use xlink:href=\"#far-image\"></use></svg><span class=\"filename\">image</span><span class=\"informations\">758\u00d7554 61 KB</span><svg class=\"fa d-icon d-icon-discourse-expand svg-icon\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><use xlink:href=\"#discourse-expand\"></use></svg></div></a></div></p>\n<p>So you can monitor progress fairly simply.</p>\n<p>Find a comfortable RPM say like 70 RPM and comfortable resistance (let\u2019s use 20 as an example) What ever you choose it should seem like it is easy for 30 minutes to an hour.</p>\n<p>Then warmup for 20 minutes and get your heart rate to say 120bpm and then track your HR for Resistance=20 RPM=70 for 10 minutes.  And then do that same test and see your heart rate after a month.  In general your heart rate should be going down and you know you are getting in better shape.  I would almost guarantee you will see improvement if you are consistent.  Once it starts feeling too easy you could change your test to be at Resistance=30.   I am just making this up these numbers to explain the concept.</p>\n<p>Same RPM same resistance after a month should be (will be) lower heart rate.</p>\n<p>If you connect to Strava, then you will have a simple way of looking at your average heart rate from minutes 20 to 30 of your \u201cMAF test\u201d workout.</p>",
